title: For Sale:  1873 Springfield Carbine
postcontent: The Springfield Model 1873 was the Army’s standard issue rifle during the Indian Wars of the 1870s and 1880s.  The rifle also saw service in the Spanish-American War and the Philippine Insurrection.  Today, it is a favorite weapon of gun collectors.In 1873, the Ordinance Department adopted the Springfield No. 99 as the standard infantry weapon of the U.S. Army.   Later designated the Springfield Model 1873 and nicknamed the “Springfield Trapdoor,”  the rifle served the American military for the next twenty years.  The rifle got its nickname from its breech-loading mechanism, which resembled a trapdoor.  To load a round, a soldier had to open the latch and manually insert a single cartridge.This M1873 has a 32 5/8-inch barrel and fired a new 45-70 cartridge.  The new round could deliver a 405 grain bullet at a muzzle velocity of 1,350 feet per second.  Not only is the cartridge an excellent anti-personnel round, it could also bring down a horse.  In addition to its impressive firepower, the M1873 is one of the first rifles to have a blued steel finish rather than the more reflective “National Armory Bright.”

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Llama IV
postcontent: I am listing a hard to find piece of Spanish firearms history, the Llama IV in 9mm or 38, with matching numbers.The gun is in fair condition. It is evident that at one point in time there was some slight surface rust, but the gun has been reblued and is currently rust free. The original grips are missing and have been replaced with some custom (more than likely homemade) target grips. The stampings are light but still visible.The Llama functions well, I test fired it with 50rds of light 38 super loads (well within the firearms original designated chamber pressures) with no apparent failures. The safety is functional, and the gun is a good copy of a 1911, sans grip safety.The model IV was the first gun produced by Llama and were not produced for the American market. The caliber is 9mm largo or 38 acp. The 38 acp is the exact same dimensionally as the 38 super auto, albeit the 38 acp is lower powered than the super. With light 38 super loads, the gun functions marvelously and all internals, including the bore, are in very good shape. It has a 5 1/2” barrel, slightly longer than a standard 1911. Production of the Llama IV started in 1932, with this specific firearm being produced in 1941. If any reference material is needed on this firearm, please email me and I will forward you to where I have found all of my information. I can also send more pictures if needed. These are extremely scarce on the American market, and it is truly a collectible that you will not find anywhere else.Asking price is $700 obo, willing to meet relatively close to Salisbury, NC.Open to any trade offers. Looking for 9mm carbines of good quality, AKs, ARs, big bore revolvers, old revolvers, military firearms... really any decent offer will be considered.
